text:
#iwantasweetersociety!! this month is human trafficking awareness month & i'm supporting a fantastic australian-owned business @sweetsocietyapparel - that's combatting human trafficking by employing women who've been rescued, giving them meaningful employment and opportunity. 
human trafficking is everwhere. it's in our supply chains, it's in the world's domestic, travel, luxury & food services. vulnerable families and people are preyed upon, men and women walk into being trafficked without even realizing and people risk their life trying to reach safety through traffickers as well. it is a sick, enormous global trade. having worked with men, women and children who've been trafficked, i have seen the huge physical & psychological damage it can cause. 
i am fortunate to have met the founder of @sweetsocietyapparel, @e_emilyanne, last year in cambodia. i am constantly inspired by people, especially women, who dedicate their lives to contributing to the greater good, which is exctly what em is doing. show some love and support her page & business - everything you do, every purchase you make, can and does make a difference! thanks to em & the girls behind sweet society & here's to doing our bit for a better world ğŸŒ

text:
odi has finally reached our 10-year milestone. we could not have done this without your support. male sexual abuse has a long lasting impact on men, especially men who are trying to navigate the social definition of masculinity. 
odi has been able to leave an imprint on the nyc community by providing free confidential support services to abuse survivors. we have also organized several panel discussions on the topic of male sexual abuse. in 2017 odi launched its monthly newsletter that addresses topics that impact male survivors. we had the largest photo exhibition of a diverse group of male survivors; phase two saw the inclusion of women. 
we ask that you join us in our celebration.  we are asking individuals to make a donation of $10 in support of our 10th anniversary. 
thank you 
dennis o tyson mpa
presdient & ceo (founder)
o'brien dennis intiative

odi has been able to leave an imprint on the nyc community by providing free confidential support services to abuse survivors. we have also organized several panel discussions on the topic of male sexual abuse. in 2017 odi launched its monthly newsletter that addresses topics that impact male survivors. we had the largest photo exhibition of a diverse group of male survivors; phase two saw the inclusion of women. 
we ask that you join us in our celebration.  we are asking individuals to make a donation of $10 in support of our 10th anniversary. 
thank you 
dennis o tyson mpa
presdient & ceo (founder)
o'brien dennis intiative

text:
when the chaotic static of my mind caused me to feel overwhelmed with the mundane world he took my hand and sat with me smiling ever so encouragingly. "make a list," he said looking into my eyes, his gentle expression comforting me in the midst of an emotional storm. "start with writing down one 'to do' item and then leave a dash underneath...but leave it blank, for now.  finish your first task then gage how you feel, if you are able to go on then write down the next 'to do' item...you do not have to do more around here than you feel comfortable with.  you can't be overwhelmed by one task at a time." he is my rock, my stability in the midst of turmoil...he helps me in such simple ways while i learn to overcome ptsd.
.
#metoo #survivor #personalhealing #ptsd #mentalhealthawarness #witch #witchlife #witchwoman #witchsofinstagram #pagan #paganwoman #pagansofinstagram #theelementsfour

text:
busy philips will always be synomous in my mind with kim kelly, the character she played in the glorious freaks and geeks but of course she is far more famous for being an instagram star. it's clear from her memoirs that she was destined or at the very least acutely determined to be famous. what sets her apart however is that she doesn't pull any punches in describing  how she broke into, survived and all but bowed out of the hollywood scene and it does leave you wondering why so many subject themselves to this perilous industry with it's endless rejection, body shaming and blatent and widespread sexism. this book harnesses the power of the #metoo movement and busy is forthright and cutthroat  in exposing many incidents of shameful behaviour she encountered/witnessed over the years. nobody is above being called out here. it is her description however of her earliest sexual encounter and the rape she suffered, a rape she wasn't even aware was rape until much later,  which i found most moving, reminding us of how we must continue to vigilent in our  discussions and educatation on the importance of consent. busy has been accused of being angry in this book and she is but she has every fucking right to be and she is highly entertaining to boot.
#thiswillonlyhurtalittle
#busyphilipps
#whatimreading 
#booklover
#audiobook
#booknerd
#instabooks
#bookreview 
#womenswriting 
#memoir

text:
#10yearchallenge
.
it may be hard to tell but a lot has changed in 10 years!
.
the girl on the left was so insecure. she was desperate to fit in and relied on other peopleâ€™s approval. she never felt good enough no matter what she did.
.
in the external world, she thought sheâ€™d already been through the hardest thing ever - seeing her parents split up. she didnâ€™t think it was her fault but she did create a lot of unworthiness around it.
.
little did she know that a few years later her brother would die. and then sheâ€™d be sexually assaulted. and then sheâ€™d lose control of her car on the highway and flip and roll into the ditch.
.
she didnâ€™t know that her unworthiness and feelings of self-doubt would continue to bring about patterns in her life that kept her feeling unworthy. she didnâ€™t understand why she kept attracting guys who didnâ€™t really care about her or respect her.
.
she had no idea what the future had in store - but i can guarantee it ended up being something she never wouldâ€™ve imagined.
.
there were also some amazing things in those 10 years... like traveling the world, working with elephants and other wildlife, studying various self-help programs, scuba diving in the philippines, meditating in the himalayas, understanding & healing her relationship with her dad, meeting some amazing people, and totally transforming her life! âœ¨
.
life is about growth and these 10 years really sum that up for me. the curveballs forced me to learn and grow in ways that most people donâ€™t.
.
i went from full-fledged drowning to fighting my way back up to the surface to grab a breath of fresh air... to drowning again, to catching my breath, over and over again.
.
until finally i stayed above the water.
.
â€œrelease to thriveâ€ came to me a couple months back because itâ€™s what i did and what i teach my clients to do. thatâ€™s why itâ€™s the name of my signature private coaching program, and also the name of my new podcast (coming soon hopefully ğŸ¤ğŸ½).
.
what do your past 10 years look like?! how much have you grown? tag me in your own 10 year challenge photo and use the hashtag #releasetothrive so i can see how youâ€™ve overcome your challenges & share your story of growth! â˜ºï¸ğŸ’•

i mean...maybe itâ€™s because iâ€™m a woman, but iâ€™m not all that offended by gilletteâ€™s new commercial. i find it condescending in a way, as it assumes all men behave badly and it comes across kinda preachy when their job is to sell shaving accessories. but iâ€™d be lying if i said this topic is something that doesnâ€™t require discussion. real talk, growing up as a young woman, iâ€™ve definitely experienced boys/men cat calling, touching me inappropriately, making sexually explicit comments about my body/shape...the whole nine. every time i expressed anger or frustration about it, i was painted as being unreasonable because i should understand that this is just what boys/ men do. i was even told that one day when iâ€™m older iâ€™d look back and appreciate that attention because as an older woman i wouldnâ€™t get it anymore! thatâ€™s madness!  while i am against todayâ€™s wave of feminism, which i believe is set up to utterly emasculate men, i am for treating women respectfully and for our being valued equally as human beings. 
with that said, i believe women must also carry ourselves respectfully and with dignity. knowing that there are some deranged men out there who will try us as women simply because theyâ€™re men is the very reason i cannot stand to see women exploit themselves! certainly, no matter what a woman wears, a man shouldnâ€™t touch her! but knowing that some men are absolute idiots with no self control, it doesnâ€™t make sense as a woman to make it that much easier (in that manâ€™s mind) to come at her sideways. these types of men will take advantage of that! 
i hate that the #metoo movement and goofy initiatives like the â€œslut walkâ€ have made it almost socially acceptable to demonize all men and paint all women as angelic victims. yet i also hate that for far too long society has turned a blind eye to certain behaviors from men as a normal part of being a man while telling women weâ€™ve just got to deal with it.

so, no. iâ€™m not offended by the commercial. but to be fair, we also need an ad to address self-respect in women and girls. not because a lack of self respect is an excuse for being disrespected...but because in this case itâ€™s pretty much expected.

this is me, standing in front of the #newyork legislature in 2017, with all of the other brave advocates who were fighting for the rights of children and adult survivors of child sexual abuse. i know how important it is that @nygovcuomo passes the #childvictimsact in the next 30 days because children shouldnâ€™t have to wait another moment to be protected on these streets. i was abused by my mother, a family member, and other people during the course of my lifetime. please show your support by calling gov. cuomo at tel: 1.518.474.8390 and urge him to pass the child victims act in the next 30 days. visit protectnykids.org for more info. 
last year, new yorkers made history at the polls by electing a democratic majority in the new york state senate.  through the efforts of dozens of coalitions and advocacy groups, in partnership with hundreds of community organizers and tens of thousands of grassroots activists -- new yorkers have changed the path of history. 
the fighting for children pac, which has been at the forefront of the effort to flip the new york senate for several years, anticipates that the passage of the child victims act will be one of the first orders of business for the next session of the new york legislature.  after passing the assembly several times in the past decade, the child victims act, which has been blocked from a vote in the formerly republican led state senate in every case, will likely finally be voted into law when the legislative session re-opens. 
but we need you to stand up and speak up for the children who are voiceless.

#metoo #timesup #kidstime #protectnykids #cuomo #newyork #legislation

text:
i remember watching the womenâ€™s march that occurred in january 2017 with tingles down my arms and tears in my eyes. i was astounded that so many women had left their homes to march in protest against being harassed, victimized, abused and assaulted. i was in awe of their bravery to speak up and use their voices to express their frustrations and to feel empowered. but i was also really saddened to see how many women had been victimized and hurt without any justice, without anyone to believe them or any comfort.
.
many women are finally coming forward and breaking their silence to divulge being victimized by powerful men and then being shamed into covering it up. itâ€™s an amazing moment to witness in history and to be a part of. so how should christians respond? sometimes, in the midst of a major shift in culture, christians find it easier to stay silent (waving my hand around here because hello iâ€™ve been guilty of that!) and change the topic. it can be hard to know how to make your voice heard.
.
this week's blog post is all about how i think christians can do a better job at responding to this major cultural shift and be an extension of the hands and feet of christ.
.
what do you think is the best way for christians to respond? let me know in the comments and full post is linked in my bio!
.
.

text:
dear ig, moving forward - can we please do the work of ending our conscious and unconscious investments in patriarchy and misogyny? itâ€™s easier said then done, but the investments and subsequent damages have to stop with us. womxn of color and girls of color have historically been the receptacles for racialized and gendered fantasies of us as either - always wanting it, not wanting it enough, passive recipients of the d or anything else, objects to be perused through, too emotional to be logical, bitches who complain too much, and/or too cocky when we stand up for ourselves or our communities. we are imagined and positioned to be receptacles. when we stand tall (especially from within) and fight back - we are too much. instead, we are supposed to be obedient and quiet girls (just to take it). see: how we were imagined during histories and current versions of colonization, imperialist wars, chattel slavery. think about the ways we, as a racialized hetero world - are invested in these characterizations of femmes of all genders. and what we do to maintain these fantasies as reality. how often do we hear, â€œdonâ€™t be a bitch?â€ or â€œsheâ€™s a bitchâ€ - b/c she said, â€œnot today.â€ or heâ€™s a bitch, because he doesnâ€™t subscribe to hypermasculinity or has her back. and what ends up the material, lived consequences of these obsessive fantasies? see: physical, sexual, emotional, financial violence. how often do we actually believe being a bitch means weakness? iâ€™ve been called a bitch in so many contexts that i have learned to say (in the words of redman), â€œiâ€™ll be that.â€ smash, divest, fuck up patriarchy. and do it first by taking inventory in the ways we are invested and implicated in it. all love and fight. for freedom, doc wun w/ you. when we know better, we do better. letâ€™s do better together. 
#aapiwomenlead #insolidarity #womenofcolor #metoo #feminism #intersectionalfeminism #eachoneteachone #timesup #abolition #docwun #teamsmakedreams #smashpatriarchy .
(image description: person with hijab and fist up center with â€œsmash patriarchyâ€).

text:
hidden issues of sexual harassment [series]: first, you are in shockâ€¦ and disbelief. how could someone whom you trust and respect behave inappropriately toward you? you worry you could be misinterpreting, but thereâ€™s no denying the truthâ€¦ this is sexual harassment. so now, what to do? always ask -tell- them to stop. maybe they will, or it may get better for awhileâ€¦ or worse.
â€¢
next, your allegiances are torn. youâ€™re a great employee and not one to stir up problems, but you decide to do the right thing and report. you ask for protection within the organization. but instead of protection, thatâ€™s when everything explodes. you feel disbelieved ~ anything but supported. false accusations may be directed against you and coworkers may ostracize you. three of four who report harassment experience retaliation.  you may be blackballed and asked/forced to leave against your will.
â€¢
â€œinstitutional betrayalâ€ happens when the company or any other organization, maybe even your church, â€œfails to protect you at a time when you might reasonably expect it to. like betrayal trauma, institutional betrayal can lead to mental and physical harm.â€ [jennifer freyd & pamela birrell, â€œblind to betrayalâ€]
â€¢
the initial betrayal by your harasser was bad enough, but now the organization has turned against you. your livelihood and career are collapsing in front of you. this is institutional betrayal, and statistics show itâ€™s a common response to reports of sexual harassment. if you [or someone you know] is trapped in such a situation â€“ realize this is abuse: stay calm, take notes, and seek legal consultation specialized in workplace law within the jurisdiction of your state as soon as possible to guide you to wise decisions.
â€¢
if this isnâ€™t you, how can you help? listen, support, never judge, never turn away - understand that a brave reporter now finds it hard to trust and feel safe. provide a job reference. connect the abuse survivor to a better career opportunity. help make others aware of the hidden injustices that result from harassment to stop it in the workplace... and the church.

text:
here are some of the faces of the survivors of abuse from r. kelly. 
another factor that played into this situation was people's instinct to separate the art from the artist. it turns out r. kelly's release of "i believe i can fly" and "i wish" were very calculated. he intentionally released songs at times where his reputation was under fire so that listeners would generally think of him with positive regard. he wanted people to be singing his songs in church so that they would later say "r. kelly? no way. he's so talented. my family loves his songs". we have a tendency to think that talent and genius = good person. .
so i have a challenge for us! stop separating the art from the artist. we started last year with hollywood and the #metoo movement. let's continue it with the music industry. i'm guilty of it too. i've idolized michael jackson my entire life, but guess who is featured in the next documentary of this kind? the "pretty young thing" star. .
#muterkelly #blacklivesmatter #sexualhealthwithdee #stopseparatingartfromartist #survivingrkelly #groomingawareness #manipulationawareness #abuseawareness #blackgirlsmatter

â¬‡ï¸
from 1870 to 1955 schools like dunbar high school in washington dcÂ equaled or scored higher on standardized test scores than white schools.

in 1950 72% of black men had been married.
in 1950 81% of black women had been married.
teenage pregnancies on decline.
black poverty was on the decline.
less black families were on government assistance.
black income was on the rise for black population in comparison to whites.
in 1965 76.4% of black children were born to married women.

text:
is this you?

we could have a to-do list with 9 out of 10 tasks ticked off and we would still obsess about the 1 that isn't done rather than acknowledge the amount of work we have completed. especially for women, we tend to be harder on ourselves and give ourselves less credit for work done. .
.
here's something you should know, your ability to appreciate who you are and what you have accomplished, affects the overall quality of your life. you must learn to enjoy the small steps you have made in the right direction and give yourself a pat on the back to say well done, so you can see the beauty and strength that has always been in you.
.
.
in my sitting room, the message on my clock says live, love, laugh as a daily reminder to focus on what is most important everyday and in every situation. 
this is your reminder to do same
.
.
you are deeply loved â¤ï¸
.
.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytic until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytic until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
in the wake of the #metoo movement, #sexualassault has been a frequently discussed topic in recent months. the growing awareness of the problem has helped to bring many cases out of the dark, and encouraged #survivors to bring charges against their #abusers. it is important for #victims of sexual assault to get the help they need to heal and recover. it is also vital that they understand their rights and how to obtain help if they decide to take #legal action against the perpetrator.

sexual assaults can have devastating effects on victims, including both physical harm and mental and emotional #trauma. these attacks are never something to take lightly or to sweep under the rug. it is a terrible situation to be faced with, and it can leave victims feeling alone, afraid, and unsure of what to do.

the man they wanted me to be will be available from @counterpointpress may 2019.

a few weeks ago i was approached with a job opportunity for an accounting position. iâ€™ve been out of work for a while and iâ€™m in desperate need because my finances are dwindling down. so, when i was approached with a possible job for a major social media influencer in beverly hills, i was thrilled and relieved. not only did the position seem perfect and i was qualified based on my experience, the pay was exactly what i was requesting and needed. the recruiter thought iâ€™d be a perfect candidate, too. i had to do some testing though before i was sent out for an interview. and, even though i had been approached on a late afternoon i was willing to do whatever was required of me. that evening i researched the employer. the name had sounded familiar but i couldnâ€™t pinpoint who he was. as he came across my screen, i totally knew who he was. i watched a few videos, googled him to see what others said about him, and checked out his instagram which displayed him dancing with several girls, other posts were he flaunted his mansion and cars but said that wasnâ€™t what he valued. he values knowledge (on how to grow your instagram account?). was i really this desperate? he annoyed me and i really didnâ€™t know what he does besides selling falsehoods and everything that is superficial and shallow.
i guess i was that desperate. i have no one helping me out. i donâ€™t have much in my savings, no retirement, nothing really. i had to push my personal thoughts aside. i knew i had dealt with different personalities, probably equivalent or worse. i could do this, i thought. so the next morning i started on the two personality tests and a comprehension test. i began the first personality test. 100 questions, choice questions (either or) to see where your personality was on different aspects, were you a narcissist or not, etc. ugh. this was getting tedious and weird. 
cont....

text:
so this is a clip from the #gillette ad which has rendered @thepiersmorgan and hundreds of thousands of others apoplectic . they see it as an attack on â€˜masculinityâ€™, another assault by swivel-eyed feminists determined to belittle the male species. 
its sad how quickly we divide into two camps- them and us, women against men.

i guess perspective is everything but when i watch the advert, i just donâ€™t see what piers and his friends see. 
i see it as being about creating a better environment for everybody -regardless of gender- but, perhaps especially for men . 
surely ,itâ€™s not about quashing masculinity but expanding and redefining masculinity?

getting rid of the macho strait jacket which forces little boys to hold back the tears , to sit on their feelings , to put on a brave face, to be â€˜one of the guysâ€™. all of those traditional stereotypes which most mental health charities agree contribute to the fact that suicide is the biggest killer of men under the age of 45
i am blessed to have and have had  many strong, capable, fearless men in my life but theyâ€™ve also been vulnerable at times, scared , unsure, in need of a shoulder to cry on .we need to give them space and permission to express that to themselves and each other and, with that freedom , they will be the best that they can be.

what do you see? .
.
.

text:
after a few questions i saw that this was his very own personality test. why i knew, they were coming from his website and i had taken personality tests before. some of these questions seemed different. more personal. and that was just it. they kept getting more personal. some questions were building upon each other, making me feel more uncomfortable as i continued. probably 50 questions in i just wanted to stop. was he serious? what he is asking is wrong. i canâ€™t recall what number this question was, i must have been more than halfway through when one of my choices were â€“ â€˜i enjoy having sex with people i hardly knowâ€™. oh my gosh! iâ€™m done, i thought. all kinds of emotions were happening. was he serious? in this age of #timesup and #metoo, doesnâ€™t he know better?
in the end of drilling through the rest of his personality test with a bunch of, â€œthatâ€™s none of your businessâ€, stopping at should i choose â€“ â€˜my body is nothing specialâ€™ or â€˜i like to look at my bodyâ€™, i completed the test and the other test, too. i sat for a minute trying to decide what i what i was 
going to do. should i just follow through and see what happens? maybe i can confront him face to face. i emailed the recruiter. i declined the position because i found his questions inappropriate, i wrote. she later called me to discuss and apologized. i never responded.
being an older woman who was raised with no gender roles, where i could do just about everything a man could do and vice versa, i wonder why things are still so unequal? i recognize the beauty i had especially in my twenties in the bright lights of hollywood and learned the hard way what that gets you. iâ€™ve made myself too aware of the statistics of crime against women inflicted by men and in my belief the crime is also being committed everyday by keeping women down, economically and socially. i became a very capable independent woman and mother that raised a young man to not see women as less than because she has different body parts.
this behavior of inappropriateness has happened for centuries where women are an object. 
cont...

text:
gillette what just happened here..?
this new advert has divided opinion unlike anything iâ€™ve seen for a while.
.
hereâ€™s my take:
.
thereâ€™s a potentially uplifting message here - but it gets lost. the way this has been put together (in my opinion) is a classic example of a failure to strike the right tone. instead of inspiring, it has offended. instead of uniting, it has spectacularly divided.
.
and the message iâ€™m referring to is a message for people, all of us. we can all treat each other better, we can all step in when we see wrongdoing, bullying, harassment. we can all take a good look at ourselves in the mirror and be good examples to our children.
.
of course there are men who need to be held accountable for their actions, just as there are women who need to be held to account for theirs. in implying the problems lie with #masculinity as a whole, men â€˜en masseâ€™ rather than specific individuals, you are in danger of being perceived to attack the very people who buy your products.
.
was it worth the risk? itâ€™s certainly the centre of attention. interested to hear othersâ€™ thoughts...
.

text:
"is this the best a man can get"? riding in on the coat-tail of the #metoo movement, @gillette has somehow compounded the trivial pursuit that is intersectional feminism, with the mundane tasks of basic male grooming.

https://youtu.be/kopmueyp3a0

the ad (link above) challenges men, boys, blacks, hispanics, pre pubescent teens, or anyone with a swinging penis between their legs to "shave off their toxic masculinity". despite a negative reception, gillette has no plans to pull the ad. in the face of social media backlash, brand director of @gillette america pankaj bhalla has repeatedly dismissed claims the ad paints men in a negative light. â€œwe recognize itâ€™s sparking a lot of passionate dialogueâ€”at the same time, itâ€™s getting people to stop and think about what it means to be our best selves, which is the point of the spot"
-pb

incorporating politically and socially charged issues into brands has become a commonly used marketing tool in what has become the "belief economy". it is however, important to note this is not the first time gillette has attempted to capitalize under the guise of altruism, as the initial gillette fortune was made marketing the safety razor the armed forces.

after patenting the obsolescent design of the safety razor in 1901. the socialist king c. gillette convinced the us military a clean shave was nesseccary to properly form a seel when wearing a gas-mask. king was awarded contract and sold 4.1 millions razors at cost, knowing the real profit would take place when returning soliders needed to replace their dull razors.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
i can't say that i differ as much in those specific years, emotion wise, what i can say is, i went from being a super happy child, to being a suicidal extremely depressed teen. constant criticism, bullying, blackmail and being used for various reasons made me feel less than dog shit. in the first 2 photos i was caring, loving, happy and most of all, naive... my experiences made me hard and cold, full of trust issues and hate for other people... it is only recently that i started letting people in again, being able to trust people, give my fullest to the people i care about and being able to stand my ground without being a psycho bitch about it (my coping method after everything i've been through), not editing my photos and now embracing who i am. it is only now that i can say with true honesty that i am happy again. what other people think of me is their problem, how i live my life is completely my choice and my mental health is my responsibility to look after.

#10yearchallenge #mylife #antibully #suicidesurvivor #beyou #beyourself #behappy #lovelife #loveyourself #inspiration #storyofmylife #stopbullying #metoo #bekind #selfharmrecovery #mentalhealth

text:
2009: 33 year old bookkeeper and mother of 3, coming out of a 19yr marriage with a pot belly, bad brows and same boring comb over, totally clueless to the outside world, who i was or the power i held. 
2019: 43yr old fake fit comptrollerâ€™s  assistant,grandmother and wife again with a slimmer waist line better brows plus traded my comb over for a thousand other styles (depending on my forever changing mood). 10 years of adventures, mistakes, naive choices and learning shaped me into the women i am today. still learning still growing no longer naive i got this. . trust it gets greater later.  #tenyearchallenge #msfakefit #greaterlater #motivation #inspiration #transformationtuesday #love #live #life #health #wealth #family #finance #glowup #blooger #lifestyle #instagood #womenempowerment #youcandoit #metoo #enddomesticviolence

kelly wants vengeance in court. 
r. kellyâ€™s life has been in shambles ever since the lifetime series surviving r. kelly debuted. the docuseries explored kellyâ€™s sexual history, which is riddled with accusations of sexual, mental, and physical assault. over 50 people were interviewed, and the long list of accusations has turned the world against r. kelly. artists he wrote songs for or collaborated with are shunning him, while two cities are asking witnesses and victims to come forward so a proper investigation can be done. radio stations are starting to ban kells music, and it appears the legend is about to watch his entire legacy disappear before his eyes. 
according to tmz, sources close to kells are claiming that he is not worried about the artists that are cutting him off and disowning him. he is dismissing artists like lady gaga, b2k, celine dion, and others as â€œphoniesâ€ who are desperate to look good in the public eye. on the other hand. kells is completely freaking out about surviving r. kelly. he sent a cease and desist letter to lifetime days before they aired the series, demanding that it be shelved. now, kells is doing everything in his power to strike back at lifetime. tmz reports he has been attempting to find dirt on executives who work for the network while he also works with a legal team to dissect the content in the docuseries.

text: last week, the american psychological association (apa) released a first-ever report entitled "guidelines for the psychological practice with boys and men"... the report defines "masculine ideaology" as "a constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the male population including: anti-femininity, achievement, eschual of the appearance of weakness, and adventure risk and violence"... further, the report says that "traditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit males' psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental and physical health"... the report also says that "conforming to the norms of "masculine ideology" can result in suppressing and masking distress in young boys as well as more risk-taking and aggressive behavior and an unwillingness to seek out help...this can lead to traits like homophobia and pave the way for sexual harassment, bullying and violence against others and themselves"... their conclusion: "traditional masculinity (i.e., "toxic masculinity") - marked by stoicism, competitiveness, dominance and aggression - is, on the whole, harmful"...what is blatantly absent in the report is a consensus definition for what it means to be a man...where is the line drawn on acceptable versus unacceptable male behavior?...i am a strong advocate for women's rights and fully support progressive movements such as #metoo and #timesup but to have a major professional organization like the apa, which i am a lifetime member of, advocate behaviors that they recklessly deem "harmful" is to further blur the increasingly fuzzy lines that distinguish the sexes...and to broad-brush many very normal male behaviors as "harmful" is irresponsible, unethical, and most of all, in my opinion, unconscionable...the above commercial was recently released by a major us corporation, gillette...it displays selective behaviors of some boys and men which are clearly wrong and unacceptable yet the implication is that this is the way the majority of men think and behave...my rebuttal of the apa report is pending...and, as of today, i'm a converted schick man...

text:
stop silencing the voice of shame and fear of stigma! 
do not wait, like i did, for over 50 years to talk about the devastating effects of abuse and violence!
this thursday, january 17, come join me, at the bookshelf in guelph, on, to get your copy and chat about the moments in my life that most disempowered me and how i was able to turn them into combustible for the engine of my life!
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

this is for my ladies s2 ep 24 surviving family is available on all podcast streaming services now! surviving family is a play on lifetime's 3 part docu-series of surviving r. kelly. there has been an uproar in the black community about the allegations and victims stories and #muterkelly. for several generations both men and women have been sexually molested and or raped by a family member and have been silenced for years and the psychological effects on the black community who have been suppressing those childhood traumas for years and masking those horrible events that took place in their lives, only for it to show up in adulthood and how they are as sexual beings. i brought @xo.tiyana on to have a healthy conversation about surviving family.
have you been a victim of child molestation or rape? do you want to share your story and positive ways to over come your childhood trauma? email me at ticiathediva@gmail.com#podcast #podcasting #podcastlife #podcasters #talkradio #blogtalkradio #women #survivingrkelly #muterkelly #survivingfamily #family #survive #molestation #rape #victims #metoo #metoomovement

text:
iâ€™ve been thinking about this so much in the last few years since giving birth to my daughters. i know i wonâ€™t be able to shield them from everything, and if iâ€™m completely honest with myself i donâ€™t want to. i know then will have close calls, awkward situations, and make a few poor life choices. but one thing i want most for them is to always feel empowered to say â€œnoâ€.
because i wasnâ€™t.
i didnâ€™t know how to express my discomfort, to get help, to use my voice. i was so worried about making a scene or causing a stir that far too many times i stayed silent. or even worse the awkward uncomfortable laugh. you know the one. where youâ€™re dying in the inside, desperately want to run but just laugh and hope the moment passes.
the laugh that comes out in â€œharmlessâ€ work exchanges, ass grabs, dirty words and peer pressure. the laugh that any other woman can instantly recognize from across the room. the laugh that makes your skin crawl because you know how horrible she feels in that moment.
so how do i empower my girls to say â€œnoâ€? what does this actually look like in practice?
a few ideas...
letting them say â€œnoâ€ to us as parents. more importantly respecting it when they do.
providing them bodily autonomy and respecting the shit out of it. teaching them to stay connected to their bodies and encourage them to express how they feel on the regular. openly and without judgement.
what are some other ways we can empower our girls to say â€œnoâ€?
â€¢
#consciousparenting
#feminist
#metoo
#raisinggirls

text:
ever since i told my sexual assault story, so many women have come to me with their #metoo moments. they have trusted me with stories they have hidden inside of them for far too long. this is for all of you brave women.

you are worthy. 
you were worthy of and deserved protection back then and you are worthy of it now. not because you are weak. heaven knows you are a survivor. because you are powerful and precious. you have a heart for infinite creation, you are divinity in human form, you are a world changer. 
you are valuable, just as you are. 
#recognizeyourworth #bestillandknow #illuminatefromwithin #youmatter

there are people who need to hear your story. there are people on the other end of your perseverance.

they are counting on you to overcome the obstacles you are facing and to be brave enough to share.

when we share our story, we give the gift of "me too." we help tangibly understand that they are not alone.

your story matters.

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
feminism discussion part 1
.
today i wanted to talk a bit about feminism. the first wave is easily defined by women's fight for voting power. thought of the second wave is often immediately followed by thought of the contraception train. but what idea or struggle is inseparable from this third wave we are now experiencing? what is it all about? or as us philosophers like to say, what is its essence?
.
in my first year of college i sat in on an art history lecture. the lesson focused in part on two visually similar but symbolically distinct paintings. the first - 'sleeping venus' by giorgione, c.1510* - was a nude of a women in a very submissive seductive pose. the second - 'olympia' by edouard manet, 1863 - also very sexual, but displayed a kind of dominance that was very controversial at that time. these artworks for me, although over 150 years old, represent the transition between a more passive role for women, & the kind of female dominance we now see.
.
discussion continued in part 2.
.

.

text:
feminism discussion part 2
.
i have caught myself stating that i disliked influencers who claim to be feminists presenting themselves in an overtly sexual manner. i felt that this was not the correct message to send young women about female empowerment. but have i missed the point? is this wave of female empowerment, like 'olympia'**, indivisible from sexual expression & dominance?
.
what exactly is third wave feminism?
.
if you call yourself a feminist it is important to know what that means, or at least, what it means to you. what do you think third wave feminism is about & what campaigns, like #metoo, do you think are a defining feature of this movement? comment below!
.

letâ€™s discuss what has been circulating in the media recently - i am sure that you all recognise r kelly, from his music back in the 2000â€™s - some may have watched the recent docu-series regarding the sexual, physical, emotional, and mental abuse that the young women were subjected to by r kelly - it is sickening to think that a man who stood as a hero and role model to many people, was capable of committing such inhumane acts - this is a harsh reminder that our women all around the world are still being abused, undervalued, disrespected and mistreated - many people involved in this case turned a blind eye and allowed the abuse to continue for many years. people covered up for him because they did want to be that one that spoke up - we must change this culture of keeping silent about issues that need to be brought to light!! survivors and victims rely on us to speak up for them when they are incapable of speaking up for themselves and we must take that responsibility seriously *a personâ€™s life could be saved!!* - 35% of women worldwide have experienced a form of violence in their lifetime. 70% of women have experienced physical or sexual violence from an intimate partner in their lifetime - these figures are shocking!! we must stand together and fight to protect our women & young girls 
#survivingrkelly #muterkelly #metoo #protectourwomen #speakout #better4kenya #thismuststop

jane walker, the female version of johnnie walkerâ€™s iconic striding man logo, is making a return for the #womenswave womenâ€™s march in washington d.c. this weekend.

johnnie walkerâ€™s â€˜striding womanâ€™ first appeared in march 2018 on limited edition bottles of johnnie walker black label, which were launched to raise awareness of gender equality issues and â€˜invite women into the brandâ€™. its introduction caused a wave of backlash from consumers, who viewed jane walker as a gimmick latching onto the #metoo and womenâ€™s rights movements.

now the striding woman is making a return on a series of placards being made available for activists to download, print off and display during the womenâ€™s march on washington on 19 january.

the signs, all of which feature the jane walker logo, include slogans such as â€˜the future is femaleâ€™, â€˜feminist dadâ€™, and â€˜with every step we gain momentumâ€™. they have been designed by a range of male and female graphic artists, including monica ahanonu, libby vanderploeg, ali macdonald, edward ubiera, laurÃ¨ne boglio, grace miceli, william de lannoy, bari schechter and laura zalewski.

diageo, brand owner of johnnie walker, said in a press release: â€˜these â€œsigns of progressâ€ aim to celebrate the spirit of the womenâ€™s movement and are inspired by the work of non-profit brand partners monumental women and she should run â€“ organisations that honour historic women who have paved the way and champion our future female leaders.â€™

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
many of the guys offended by the gillette advert don't actually look like they need a shave. saying "i hate burned cheeseburgers" doesn't mean you hate all cheeseburgers, or that all cheeseburgers are burned. saying "i hate toxic masculinity" doesn't mean you hate masculinity, or that all masculinity is toxic. you can still be masculine and not have to adhere to old fashioned and virulent tropes. some people will never understand how important it is to change the way some men act and how it reflects on others. all of you soggy boys outraged by a brand man enough to tell other men their behaviour is unacceptable might want to check yourselves. yes itâ€™s a little bit schmaltzy and overwrought but the replies from men who are clearly fragile and terrified of being criticised is proof of how much campaigns like this are needed.

complaining that the advert is bad because it tells men theyâ€™re â€˜not good enoughâ€™ ğŸ¤” welcome to literally every advert ever targeted at women. at least youâ€™re not good enough because of your actions. 
women just suck because of their skin/hair/weight/face.

toxic masculinity is not the problem. 
lack of genuine masculinity is.

visit titaniapaige.com or click the link in my bio to hear jessicaâ€™s story and her wisdom concerning confession and accountability for porn addiction.

text:
get ready for another women's march in bergen!
*
in recent years, we have witnessed an unacceptable rhetoric about women, religion, immigration, ethnicity, and climate challenges; and in 2019, we still have many reasons to march: *
#metoo. the inauguration of supreme court judge brett kavanaugh. the abortion act used as a negotiation card here in norway. larry nassar. the inauguration of brazil's new president jair bolsonaro. attacks on female public figures. no to a consent law in norway. the list is long - and we refuse to just stand and watch!
*
we also want to support and honor the nobel peace prize winners of 2018, denis mukwege mukengere and nadia murad, in their fight against the use of rape and sexual violence as a weapon of war.
*
we will send a clear message to the new us administration, to our own administration - and to the rest of the world - that women's rights are human rights, and human rights are women's rights.
*
this is #whyimarch!
*
this year's main subject: the female body under attack.
*
*
#womensmarchbergen #wmb #womensmarch #womenswave #wmb2019 #metoo #timesup #believesurvivors #believewomen

text: in my world, i am beginning to see the softening of the masculine. care and nurturance and open communication; gentleness. my brother always had this quality and the bar was set high for most other men in my life. now i see more of it from my father, my old time male friends, new friends, my son and maybe i will even see it from my ex- husband. something i have been asking for - perhaps since the day i was born. the divine masculine is rising. the shift is here. a thousand times thank you to all those who did the work and continue to; the heavyweights that carry the burden. please note the picture was taken by a friend not on instagram. #divinemasculine #theshift #rishikesh #gangaaarti #themeekshallinherittheearth #metoo #metoomovement

"we believe". it was unilever that first introduced social responsibility into packaged goods advertising with dove's self-esteem project, but procter & gamble grabbed that ball a few years back and have been running with it ever since. that underlying message has gradually been rolling out to different brands, finally reaching gillette on this the 30th anniversary of that long-established brand slogan "the best a man can get". in an age of #metoo and more, grey new york questions many of the existing assumptions about what truly makes for the "best" from men. needless to say, gillette's status remains unchallenged even if casual sexism, bullying, mansplaining and apparently even barbecues are a strict no-no. director kim gehrig does a fine job of corralling the elements: she's become the go-to for these types of campaigns, last seen on that fine "viva la vulva" campaign for essity, featured here late last year. we can only show 60 seconds here so come see us at https://www.adbrands.net for the full film.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
this quote to me,  is dumb. i didn't get to be 148kg by having fun. i used food and alcohol to mask my emotions and fill voids in my life. i used them as coping mechanisms and i let myself neglect my health and self worth by eating myself to obesity. 
i did it to "protect myself". when i was 18 i was violently sexually assaulted. my vagina and labia was so damaged after my encounter with someone i considered a close friend that i was not able to walk properly for weeks. this all happened when i 'was beautiful'. i was fit and healthy and proud of my body; and now i've spent the last 7+ years eating to hide myself. i never wanted to feel like that again. 
but i'm sick of feeling like this now.  i want to be happy,  and carefree again.  i want to have children and not worry about my health. o.m. you did not ruin my life. i will not let that one night continue to hold me back.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text: 'silence, like dante's hell, has its concentric circles. first come the internal inhibitions, self-doubts, repressions, confusions, and shame that make it difficult to impossible to speak, along with the fear of being punished or ostracized for doing so. susan brinson, now chair of the philosophy department at dartmouth, was raped in 1990 by a man, a stranger, who called her a whore and told her to shut up before choking her repeatedly, bashing her head with a stone, and leaving her for dead. afterwards she found various problems in talking about the experience: "it was one thing to have decided to speak and write about my rape, but another to find the voice with which to do it. even after my fractured trachea had healed, i frequently had trouble speaking. i was never entirely mute, but i often had bouts of what a friend labelled 'fractured speech' during which i stuttered and stammered, unable to string together a simple sentence without the words scattering like a broken necklace."' rebecca solnit â¤ï¸

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

gillette references toxic masculinity, bullying, and the #metoo movement in their new advert, and it has split opinion online. the short film titled believe, encourages men to be "the best a man can be". also questioning the 'boys will be boys' attitude towards raising boys and girls differently. 
gillette's president, gary coombe has said that 'by holding each other accountable, eliminating excuses for bad behaviour, and supporting a new generation working toward their personal 'best,' we can help create positive change that will matter for years to come'.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn
